sentences: Take 6 is an American a cappella gospel sextet formed in 1980 on the campus of Oakwood College in Huntsville, Alabama.
Oakwood College years =

In 1980, Claude McKnight, older brother of R&B musician Brian McKnight, formed an a cappella quartet, The Gentlemen's Estates Quartet, at Oakwood College (now Oakwood University), a Seventh-day Adventist university in Huntsville, Alabama, where he was a freshman.

In 1980, Claude McKnight, older brother of R&B musician Brian McKnight, formed an a cappella quartet, The Gentlemen's Estates Quartet, at Oakwood College (now Oakwood University), a Seventh-day Adventist university in Huntsville, Alabama, where he was a freshman.
He joined the harmonizing, adding a fifth part with them onstage that night.
In 1985, the lower half of the group (bass, baritone, and second tenor) left after graduating.
The band signed a contract with Warner Alliance in 1987 and changed its name to Take 6 after a search revealed the name "Alliance" was in use.
Their eponymous debut album (1988) won Grammy Awards in the gospel and jazz categories and three Dove Awards.
The band's second album, So Much 2 Say (1990) appeared on the gospel, jazz, and R&B charts of Billboard magazine.
In 1991, after the release of So Much 2 Say, Mervyn Warren left the group to pursue a career as a record producer and was replaced by Joey Kibble, Mark Kibble's younger brother.
The group added instrumentation to their a cappella sound on the album He Is Christmas.
In 2006, the group started the label Take 6 Records; Feels Good, the first album on their new label, was released the same year.
In 2006, the group started the label Take 6 Records; Feels Good, the first album on their new label, was released the same year.
In 2007, they recorded with Eros Ramazzotti for his album E².
A year later Take 6 released The Standard, which ventured into more traditional jazz territory.
Believe (Sono, 2016), produced by Claude Villani and Ross Vannelli, charted in six categories on Billboard in its first two weeks of release.

Iconic (Sono, 2018), produced and arranged by the band, was its first album to chart at No. 1 on the Billboard Contemporary Jazz Chart.
